apid economic development and how the relationship between Europe and Asia shifted in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.Though the Company held a monopoly on English overseas trade to Asia, the Court of Directors extended the right to trade in Asia to their employees, creating an unusual situation in which employees worked both for themselves and for the Company as overseas merchants. Building on the organizational infrastructure of the Company and the sophisticated commercial institutions of the markets of the East, employees constructed a cohesive internal network of peer communications that directed English trading ships during their voyages. This network integrated Company operations, encouraged innovation, and increased the Company's flexibility, adaptability, and responsiveness to local circumstance.Between Monopoly and Free Trade highlights the dynamic potential of social networks in the early modern era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness & EconomicsxInternationalxEconomics. 0aBusiness & EconomicsxInternationalxGeneral. 0aBusiness & EconomicsxReference. 0aCapitalismxHistoryy17th century. 0aCapitalismxHistoryy18th century. 0aCorn laws (Great Britain). 0aFree tradezGreat Britain. 0aHistoryzEuropezGreat Britain. 0aSocial networks. 0aTariffzGreat Britain. 0zGreat BritainxColoniesxAmericaxCommerce. 0zGreat BritainxColoniesxEconomic conditions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aAsian commercial institutions.  aAsian merchants.  aAsian ports.  aAsian trading ports.  aCourt of Directors.  aEnglish East India Company.  aEnglish trade patterns.  aEurope.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aalternative explanations.  aanalytical sociology.  achoosing ports.  acommercial networks.  acomparative analysis.  acorruption.  